Observation Details: We have two Tree Swallows who pretty much claimed our nest box as soon as they arrived, which makes me think they must be the same ones who have returned, this time for the third year in a row.  They successfully fledged young in 2016, but despite laying 2 eggs in 2017, it was a bust due to the incessant strong winds which made it difficult for them to find food.  They have been copulating since May 22nd.  Today they had 3 marauding Tree Swallows attempt a hostile take over of the nest box.  High back yard drama.

This is the last day the TRSW eggs in our nest box were safe.  Witnessed (3) fights between the Swallows and a male HOSP.  One (1) TRSW, possibly  the mother, successfully pinned the HOSP to the lid of the nest box.  Undeterred I watched as the HOSP rode the back of a TRSW as it flew along the ground into a Raspberry patch about 30 feet north of the box.  After witnessing three (3) fights with by this  persistent House Sparrow, the mother seemed to have disappeared  for the rest of the day.  By 10 O-clock, I noticed that there were some Goose feathers on the ground, so I inspected the box fearing the worst, but the eggs were still warm and covered by large feathers, which I presume were Goose or Duck feathers.  The Father TRSW survived and hung around for a couple of days, but next time I checked the box, four (4) of the eggs were missing and one was damaged.  The other three were cold.  The assertive male HOSP was now patrolling the fence ledge as if to make claim to the box for himself.

Observation Details: We have two Tree Swallows who pretty much claimed our nest box as soon as they arrived, which makes me think they must be the same ones who have returned, this time for the third year in a row.  They successfully fledged young in 2016, but despite laying 2 eggs in 2017, it was a bust due to the incessant strong winds which made it difficult for them to find food.  They have been copulating since May 22nd.  Today they had 3 marauding Tree Swallows attempt a hostile take over of the nest box.  High back yard drama.

3 Adults seen chasing a Merlin, but feeding visits seem further spaced apart.  From 8:17 am to 8:46 am there were 13 feedings.  I stopped counting and went inside, then returned and counted 9 feedings from 9:11 am to 9:38 am.  There usually was one young Swallows present in the hole of the nest box accepting several insect transfers in a row.  It would then disappear and either the same chick or a different one would occupy the spot.  Sometimes the parent would refuse to feed the chick, chase it back inside and then go inside herself, sometimes returning with a fecal sack.  Prey species of Insects includes Moths (reddish color may indicate that these are Forest Tent Caterpillar Moths) and both black & red Dragonflies.

Media notes: Photo taken on May 23rd, 2018
Observation Details: We have two Tree Swallows who pretty much claimed our nest box as soon as they arrived, which makes me think they must be the same ones who have returned, this time for the third year in a row.  They successfully fledged young in 2016, but despite laying 2 eggs in 2017, it was a bust due to the incessant strong winds which made it difficult for them to find food.  They have been copulating since May 22nd.  Today they had 3 marauding Tree Swallows attempt a hostile take over of the nest box.  High back yard drama.

Observation Details: They were investigating the abandoned Downy nest hole in the willow tree. The both went into it (separately), and then chirped at each other on a branch. Pretty clear they were discussing real estate.Not sure if we call this"Pair in habitat" or "Visiting probable nest site".  Deb Allen tells me Tree Swallows haven't nested in the park sine 1868, so this is pretty exciting. However, I worry about the proximity of House Sparrow nests, one of which is along the same limb, in the "elbow" at the bottom. I think that's why the Downies abandoned the hole, which they had excavated earlier in the Spring..

Le 15 novembre vers la fin de l’avant-midi, j’ai observé 25 Hirondelles bicolores s’alimenter dans la baie du Récré-O-Parc de Ville de Sainte-Catherine, l’une de celles-ci est venue se poser juste à côté de moi ce qui m’a permis de voir sur son front deux morceaux de glace. Pendant sa pose au sol qui a duré environ 10 minutes, j’ai vu l’Hirondelle bicolore tourner sa tête et placer son bec dans son plumage. La température au Récré-O-Parc à 11h00 était -7 °C et avec le facteur vent température ressentie -12° C.

Observation Details: Adults flying around and feeding fledglings.

3 Adults seen chasing a Merlin, but feeding visits seem further spaced apart.  From 8:17 am to 8:46 am there were 13 feedings.  I stopped counting and went inside, then returned and counted 9 feedings from 9:11 am to 9:38 am.  There usually was one young Swallows present in the hole of the nest box accepting several insect transfers in a row.  It would then disappear and either the same chick or a different one would occupy the spot.  Sometimes the parent would refuse to feed the chick, chase it back inside and then go inside herself, sometimes returning with a fecal sack.  Prey species of Insects includes Moths (reddish color may indicate that these are Forest Tent Caterpillar Moths) and both black & red Dragonflies.

Behaviour change noted:  Sometimes chicks are now meeting parents at the hole with yelllow gape open.  Noted that Swallow Prey species has included red Dragonflies and Reddish Brown Moths - probably Forest Tent Caterpillar Moths.  Also surprising was the attitude of the parent Swallows to the Jack Rabbit that has been hanging around our yard lately.  They aggressively dive bombed the jack Rabbit in an effort to chase it away.  Does the Jack Rabbit pose a real threat to the fledglings?

Media notes: Now we have 7 eggs. Observation Details: Last photo of eggs was taken on May 29th to check nest after House Sparrows had possibly entered box.  This time a Common Grackle was on the nest box and being attacked the Tree Swallows.  Again we were unsure as to the condition of the eggs and so took the opportunity to photograph the nest, since they were already disturbed by the Grackle.  As I took the photo I was swooped at by 3 Tree Swallows, so there may be 2 fathers of these eggs.  We have been seeing 5 Tree Swallows in the vicinity over the past few weeks.
